# Terminal Lessons AI Rules

These rules are permanent project instructions for AI agents working in this repository.

## Skill: Documenting And Implementing Features

Trigger: Any request to add, change, fix, refactor, or complete an app feature.

Workflow:
- Keep OS-level logic in Go backend code. This includes PTY/session handling, filesystem and workspace operations, lesson import/storage, YAML validation, check execution, process cleanup, and Wails event emission.
- Keep UI logic in React frontend code. This includes Xterm.js rendering, panels, controls, visual state, hint reveal, check-result display, and user interaction flows.
- Use Wails bound methods for frontend-to-backend commands and Wails runtime events for backend-to-frontend streaming/status updates.
- When changing Go structs returned to the frontend or any bound Go methods, remind the user to run `wails generate module`.
- When a feature is complete, update `docs/architecture.md` with the feature behavior and any interface changes.
- When adding or changing Wails events, document the event name and exact payload shape in `docs/architecture.md`.
- When a phase or task is complete, check it off in `AGENTS.md`.
- Prefer tests near the changed subsystem:
  - Go: `go test ./...`
  - Frontend: `pnpm --dir frontend test`
  - Frontend build: `pnpm --dir frontend build`
  - Full desktop build: `CGO_ENABLED=1 wails build`
- For macOS/Wails builds in this repo, use a PATH that includes Go, Wails, Node, pnpm, and `/usr/sbin`.

## Skill: Curriculum Developer / Lesson Generation

Trigger: The user asks to create a new exercise, task, lesson, terminal challenge, or curriculum item.

Output contract:
- Generate a YAML lesson that conforms to this schema shape:

```yaml
version: 1
id: "safe-unique-lesson-id"
title: "Human-readable lesson title"
commands: ["command1", "command2"]
difficulty: "beginner"
intro: "Clear learner-facing task instructions."
workspace:
  files:
    - path: "relative/path.txt"
      content: "Initial file content\n"
hints:
  - "First hint."
  - "Second hint."
solution:
  commands:
    - "example command for learner reference only"
  explanation: "Why the solution works."
checks:
  - type: "file_equals"
    path: "relative/output.txt"
    expected: "Expected content\n"
```

Strict rules:
- Never generate executable shell scripts, arbitrary execution code, setup scripts, teardown scripts, or test scripts inside lesson YAML.
- `solution.commands` are educational reference only and must not be treated as executable test logic.
- All paths must be safe relative paths.
- Never use absolute paths.
- Never use `..` path traversal.
- Never include null bytes or platform-specific dangerous path tricks.
- Keep generated workspace files small and focused.
- Prefer deterministic checks that inspect files or terminal transcript text.
- Use `trim: true` only when leading/trailing whitespace should not matter.

Permitted check types:
- `file_exists`
- `file_not_exists`
- `file_equals`
- `file_contains`
- `stdout_contains`
- `stdout_matches`

Check rules:
- `file_exists`, `file_not_exists`, `file_equals`, and `file_contains` require a safe relative `path`.
- `file_equals` and `file_contains` use `expected`.
- `stdout_contains` uses `expected`.
- `stdout_matches` uses `pattern` as a regular expression.
- Do not invent new check types unless the backend is updated first and `docs/architecture.md`, `docs/lesson.schema.json`, `docs/lesson-authoring.md`, and `AGENTS.md` are updated.
